<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910705-0020</DOCNO><DOCID>910705-0020.</DOCID><HL>   GE Accords Provide   For 13.5% Pay Raise   Over Term of 3 Years</HL><DATE>07/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9</SO><CO>   GE LABOR</CO><MS>CONGLOMERATES (CGL)INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>CONGLOMERATES (CGL)ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)</IN><NS>LABOR, PERSONNEL ISSUES, TRENDS, MANAGEMENT TECHNIQUES (LAB)</NS><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   FAIRFIELD, Conn. -- General Electric Co. said that undertentative labor contracts with two unions representing 44,000GE employees, the average pay will rise 13.5% over the threeyears of the pacts.   Terms, reached Saturday, call for three general payincreases, and five cost-of-living increases based on ananticipated inflation rate of about 3.8% annually, GE said.Under the previous contract, which expired June 30, averagepay for the union workers increased 11.8%.</LP><TEXT>   The new contracts also renew an early retirement optionprogram created in 1988. It offers employees with 25 years inthe company an option to retire at age 55 with fullretirement benefits if they face a layoff. In another newjob-security provision, the two sides agreed to a &quot;plantclosing pension option&quot; under which employees between 50 and59 years old affected by a plant closing will be offeredlifetime income and full pension benefits.   The national contracts were reached with the InternationalUnion of Electronic Workers and the United Electrical Workersof America. GE said union leadership recommended approval ofthe accord, which is to be voted on Wednesday.   GE is separately negotiating, on a plant-by-plant basis,with 10 other unions representing about 21,000 employees. Themanufacturer, broadcaster and financial services providersaid those local talks are expected to conclude this month.   The national contracts negotiated with the IUE and UE formthe basis for pay changes for production employees beyond the65,000 union workers. The benefit portion of the contractsapplies to most of GE's 235,000 domestic employees.</TEXT></DOC>